The '''UK-ASEAN Business Council''' (UKABC) is a [[non-profit organization|non-profit]] organisation founded in 2011. It was originally created by the UK government in order to facilitate trade and business relations between the [[United Kingdom]] and [[ASEAN]].

The UKABC helps UK businesses looking to find out more about the opportunities in [[Southeast Asia]], and those wanting to start doing business there. The UKABC raises awareness of the commercial opportunities in ASEAN, and provides facilitated networking opportunities with senior ASEAN commercial and political decision makers to encourage discussion and negotiation with the aim of furthering multi-national trade.<ref name="ukabc.org.uk">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/trade-mission-to-singapore-and-indonesia-to-boost-exports|title=Trade mission to Singapore and Indonesia to boost exports|last=|first=|date=11 March 2013|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=|work=gov.uk}}</ref> They also provide structured business-to-business meetings, often with senior political and commercial decision makers.{{who|date=January 2016}}

UKABC works in partnership with the [[Department for International Trade]] (formerly [[UK Trade & Investment]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ukti.blog.gov.uk/author/uk-asean-business-council/|title=UK-ASEAN Business Council|work=UKTI blog}}</ref>

The UK-ASEAN Business Council is a sister organisation to the [[UK India Business Council]] and the [[China–Britain Business Council]].

==History==
UKABC was created out of [[UK Trade & Investment]]'s strategy "Britain Open for Business", was launched by [[Vince Cable|Dr Vince Cable]] in November 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/294090/Britain_open_for_business_-_UKTI_s_five_year_strategy_1_.pdf|title=Britain Open for Business|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=UK Trade & Investment|page=72|access-date=27 January 2017}}</ref> In 2015, The UK-ASEAN Business council moved from within the [[Department for Business, Innovation & Skills]] into [[Millbank Tower]], and became a [[private company]].

As of January 2016, The UK-ASEAN Business Council had partnerships with the [[Department for International Trade]], [[Benoy]], [[HSBC]], [[Jardine Matheson|Jardines]], NashTech, [[Pearson PLC|Pearson]], [[Prudential plc|Prudential]], [[PwC]], and [[Royal Dutch Shell|Shell]].<ref name="SP">{{cite web|url=http://www.ukabc.org.uk/our-partners/|title=UK- ASEAN Business Council Partners|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=UKABC|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=29 January 2016}}</ref>

